default&#xa0;default1.   defaultQ1: Are crimes being recorded by the police when they should be? Are crimes being categorised correctly?default1.1default 
defaultThe short answer to 
defaultboth 
defaultthese questions is 
default“
defaultno
default”.
default1.2default 
defaultThe Natio
defaultnal Crime Recording Standard (NCRS) was introduced in April 2002 in order to ensure that police forces across the country were recording crime to a common standard. The then 
defaultHome 
defaultSecretary David Blunkett stated that this was a fundamental requirement if cr
defaultime was to be tackled effectively.   It was also believed that it would increase trust in the police as victims’ needs would be paramount in such a system
default. The 
defaultNCRS 
defaultstates:
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe aim of NCRS is todefault&#xa0;defaultbe victim focused and maintain a consistent data set of defaultrecordeddefault&#xa0;defaultcrime allegations across all forces.default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default 
defaultFollowing the initial registration, an incident will be recorded as a crime (notifiable offence) if, on the balance of probability:default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default(a) thedefault defaultcircumstances as reported amount to a crime defined by law (the defaultpolice will determine this, based on their knowledge of the law and counting rules), and (b) there is no credible evidence to the contrary.default(Home Office 2006: Appendix A)default1.3default 
defaultPrior to the introduction of the NCRS an ‘evidential’ crime recording standard wa
defaults being applied. This involved victims having to convince the police that a crime had actually occurred. 
defaultIn effect officers were treating victims as suspects. 
defaultThis system had a long history of abuse as officers
default 
defaultemployed a number of dubious measures to ensu
defaultre 
defaultreported crimes
default didn’t appear in the official returns. These included
default:
default&#xa0;
default1.4default 
defaultWrongly categorising more serious crimes as lesser offences is also a way of hitting key targets such as burglary reduction. These would include
default:
default&#xa0;
default1.5default 
defaultThese methods are collectively known in police circles as ‘cuffing’ after the magician’s art of making objects dis
defaultap
defaultpear up their 
defaultsleeve or cuff (Young 1991).
default 
default1.6default 
defaultWhist the NCRS enjoyed a brief period of success from 2002-2004 it suffered from a re
default-
defaultinterpretation from 2004 onwards. 
defaultThis 
defaultcan be traced back to
default the 
defaultthen Prime Minister Tony Blair’s 
defaultinitiative
default to reduce street crime. Dur
defaulting this 
defaultoperation
default,
default involving the twelve forces with high robbery rates
default,
default it became evident that victims of robberies involving mobile phones were reporting these offences sometime after the incident. It was also discovered that mobile phone providers were 
defaultadvising victims to report 
defaulttheir 
defaultphones 
defaultas 
defaultstolen in order to validate their insurance
default claim
default. 
defaultDespite the evidence from the British Crime Survey that victims of robberies are reluctant to report
default 
defaultthe
defaultse crimes
default to the police
default,
default 
defaultwith 
defaultonly 
default51%
default reporting 
default robber
defaultie
defaults to the police 
default(
defaultDodd et al default2004:38default)
default, 
defaultthose officers co
default-
defaultordinating the street crime initiative convinced themselves that a high percentage of reported robberies were false reports in pursuit of bogus insurance claims. This led to the introduction of ‘false
default reporting’ policies which required victims to prove the
defaulti
defaultr report was genuine. In effect a return to an ‘evidential’ crime recording standard. 
default1.7default 
defaultThis in turn led to a re-interpretation of the NCRS where the 
defaultoverriding 
defaultvictim focussed emphasis was replac
defaulted by the secondary conditions
default,
default 
defaultinitially 
defaultrelating to third party reports, based on a ‘balance of probability’ test carried out by the police. The evidence (Patrick 2011a) suggests this re-interpretation spread from robberies to all offences and then from 
defaultforce to force.  The impact on the recorded crime rates is evident from the analysis of Nottinghamshire’s recorded crime
default profile (Fig. 1)
default  
default1.8default 
defaultThe Nottinghamshire data (Fig 1) shows a significant rise in 2001 corresponding with an HMIC inspection report
default (HMIC/Notts 2001) criticising their recording procedures which were clearly based on an ‘evidential’ standard. The sudden fall in 2004/05 corresponds with the introduction of false reporting procedures and would suggest a return to the previous ‘evidentia
defaultl’ standard of crime recording.    
default  
default1.9default 
defaultSimilar patterns are 
defaultclear
default from an analysis of other forces where evidence of a shift back to an ‘evidential’ standard and associated ‘cuffing’ has emerged.  
defaultA report in the Daily Mail 
default( 6.5.08default) defaultcontained a revelat
defaultion from a police ‘whistle blower’ that officers in Norfolk had been instructed not to record reports of criminal damage unless the victim could prove it was not accidental
default. This 
defaulthad a dramatic impact on the levels of criminal damage in that force (Fig. 2)
default. Again the return to pre NCRS levels is significant.  
default  
default 
default 
default(FIG. 2)
default1.10default 
defaultMore recently the Police and Crime Commissioner of Gwent cited un
default-
defaultreliable crime recording as grounds for asking the Chief Constable to retire
default.
default The 
defaultHMIC audit of crime recording procedures suggested 
default‘cuffing’ was occurring:
default              default“HMIC looked at 120 incidents logged by Gwent Police. Seventeen had been wrongly default              defaultclosed without a crime being raised, which indicated that crime recording in Gwent gives default              defaultcause fdefaultor concern.” HMIC/Gwent 2012default1.11default 
defaultThe same report indicated recorded crimes were also being wrongly categorised
default and the authors were 
defaultclear on where the blame lay:
default              default“The quality of crime and incident data would be significantly improved if there were default              defaultgreatdefaulter clarity and focus from chief officers and the police authority on the importance of default              defaultthe issue.” HMIC/Gwent 2012default1.12default 
defaultFurther
default evidence of ‘cuffing’ emerged in Kent in 2012 when HMIC investigated the force 
defaultafter
default an officer ‘blew the whistle’ on
default ‘gaming’ 
defaultbehaviours designed to improve the detection rate. 
default1.13default 
defaultThe Chief Constable of Kent, who had previously served in Norfolk, announced his retirement in October 2013
default.
default 
default1.14default The 
defaultresearch on which this submission is based
default w
defaultas
default recently corroborated by a report from the Office for National Statistics: 
default              default“Given the consistent pattern, one possible hypothesis is that there has been a gradual default              defaulterosion of compliance with the NCRS such that a growing number of crimes reported to the default              defaultpolice are not being captured in crime recording systems. There are a range of possible default              defaultdrivers for this including: default&#xa0;default              default• lack of awareness or adequate understanding of the NCRS as time passes from its launch default              defaultleading to some officers recording ‘as chargedefaultd’ or ‘if detected’ which might result from default              defaultstaff turnover and lack of sufficient on-going training; default&#xa0;default              default• performance pressures associated with targets (e.g. to reduce crime or increase default              defaultdetection rates) acting as perverse incentives for some crimes to bedefault downgraded from default              defaultnotifiable into non-notifiable categories or as ASB or as crime-related incidents (which are default              defaultnot captured in data returned to the Home Office); default&#xa0;default              default• though forces have continued with their own internal audits, the cessation of default              defaultindependedefaultnt audits from 2006/07 onwards may have reduced the focus on addressing non-default              defaultcompliance; default&#xa0;default              default• the move to Neighbourhood Policing in recent years may also have led to more low level default              defaultcrimes being dealt with informally and outside the formal crime recording defaultsystem; and, default&#xa0;default              default• in the context of pressure on police budgets and a general policy shift to promote greater default              defaultofficer discretion, a return to a more evidential recording model”default default              default              default              default              default              default              default              default              default(Flatley and Bradley 2013:12)default&#xa0;default1.15default 
defaultWhilst th
defaultis
default submission is technical 
defaultin nature, 
defaultthe human cost of such perverse behaviour should not be overlooked. The failure to record crimes prevents 
defaultoffences
default being investigated and offenders brought to justice. 
default In a number of cases this has 
defaultallowed 
defaultcriminals
default 
defaultfre
defaulte rein to commit serious crimes, including murder
default. 
default 
defaultIn 2006 the IPCC investigated the contact Colette Lynch had with Warwickshire police prior to her death. In this case it emerged Warwickshire officers failed to record 
defaultand investigate a report of criminal
default damage involving the victim’s estranged partner. The IPCC made the following comment on the force’s crime recording procedures:
default “A review should be undertaken of the extent to which those who are required to implement the policies on domestic violence, crime recording and call handling are aware of their responsibilities.” (IPCC 2006:5)     default&#xa0;
