default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default2. defaultQ2. What are the factors which can influence defaultmdefaultis-recording of crime?default&#xa0;
default2.1default Performance Management as a system of control has since its inception been vulnerable to ‘gaming’ type behaviours A
defaultr
defaultgy
defaultr
defaultis a leading expert conclud
defaulted
default:
default&#xa0;
default              default“the dream of many management information system designers is to design a default              defaulttamper-default              defaultproof, guaranteed-to-catch-the-culprit information system. default defaultIf they succedefaulteddefault, they will also default              defaultsucceed in superimposing on defensive routines a control system that will call the default              defaultindividuals to new heights of creativity on how to bypass the threatening features of the default              defaultinformation system.” (Adefaultrdefaultgyris 1985:147) default&#xa0;default2.2default The advent of ‘false reporting’ pol
defaulticies and associated re-interpretation of the NCRS is an example of this theory in action.
default The fact that Performance Management systems are a threat to the leadership of the service explains the involvement of 
defaultc
defaulthief 
defaulto
defaultfficers in the re-interpretation of the
default NCRS. Once th
defaulte NCRS
default was undermined
default 
defaultthen pressure could be applied throughout the system to ensure that 
defaultobstacles were placed in the way of victims and offic
defaulters under-record
defaulted
default crime
default. 
default 
default&#xa0;
default2.3default 
defaultOfficers are fully aware of how the system operates and also know 
defaultthat if something goes wrong then senior officers will deny any knowledge or complicity
default.
default This phenomenon is referred to as
default ‘organisational hypocrisy’ default(Ericson 1981).
default2.4default 
defaultResearch has also established that 
defaultsending an officer to assess every report of crime 
defaultresults in less crimes being recorded: 
default“It seems plausible that crime allegations dealt with by telephone investigation are more likely to be accepted ‘at face value’ by the police. By comparison, it is inevitable that where police officers do attend crimdefaulte scenes they will be in a position to be more discriminating about allegations made” (Burrows et 2000:28)default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default2.default5default 
defaultThey went on to conclude
default:
default“If the hypothesis posed by the research team – that forces which attend more crime scenes will tend to record fewer defaultcrime allegations (or categorise offences more rigorously) – is credible, this factor is likely to influence that force’s low crime rate” (Burrows et al 2000:29).default2.default6default 
defaultThis could explain why sending an officer to every reported crime has been adopted by a 
defaultnumber of forces claiming impressive reductions in recorded crime
default e.g. Merseyside, Essex 
defaultand
default Kent
default. Of course this policy is 
defaultpresented
default as good practice in customer care.  
