defaultal Crime Survey. However they stopped 
defaultpublishing the results 
defaultin 2006 
defaultwhen it 
defaultbecame
default clear 
defaultrecording rates were falling
default:
default     
default&#xa0;
default“Comparing with the previous year, there have been reductions in the estimated recording rate for burglary (77% to 64%), bicycle theft (62% to 54%) and robbery (53%default defaulttodefault default44%)default”default (Walker et al 2006:47)default3.4default defaultIn 2005 I had alerted the National Crime Registrar to t
defaulthe suspicion that the NCRS was being interpreted literally and the ‘balance of probability’ rule applied to all reports. This senior statistician’s role was to oversee and offer guidance on the NCRS and at that time he was of the opinion that victim sovere
defaultignty was still the overriding consideration and the ‘balance of probability’ test was only to be used in relation to third party reports
default. However
default at a further meeting in 2006 the same individual confirmed the ‘balance of probability’ test was in fact bein
defaultg applied universally.  It should be noted that at the time of the second meeting th
defaultis official
