default4. defaultQ4. Has enough been done to ensure the integrity of crime data? What more should be done?default&#xa0;default4.1default 
defaultThe fact that police officers are openly admitting that they are ‘fiddling the figures’ 
defaultsuggests not enough has been done.
default&#xa0;
default4.2default The research I conducted on this topic 
default(Patrick 2011b)
default 
defaultled me to the conclusion that too close a relationship between Chief Offi
defaultcers of Police and those responsible for their governance and regulation led to what Hood and Bevan (2006) referred to as a Nelson’s eye approach to scrutiny. This was manifestly clear from the response to the HMIC audit of detections 
default(Appendix A) 
defaultwhich le
defaultd to ACPO approaching the Information Commissioner. The correspondence between ACPO and the Information Commissioner makes it self-evident th
defaultere was 
defaulta reluctance to expose critic
defaultal
default failings
default (Appendix B)
default.
default   
default&#xa0;
default4.3default 
defaultThe shift in responsibility for publishing c
defaultrime statistics from the Home Office to the Office for National Statistics appears to have stimulated the report by Flatley and Bradley
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
default4.4default The problem with the ‘looseness’ introduced to the NCRS through its re
default-
defaultinterpretation as an universal ‘balance of
default probability’ 
defaultstandard
default 
defaultneeds to be addressed
default. This can be achieved by moving to a ‘prima facia’ standard ensuring that all offences reported are recorded as crimes. In the past this approach has been adopted by forces caught manipulating their figures 
defaultthus 
defaultdemonstrating that if sufficiently incentivised chief officers are capable of delivering accurate data.
default&#xa0;
default4.5default 
defaultThere needs to be 
defaultan 
defaulteffective
default, fully 
defaultindependent audit regime with statutory powers to inspect
default, require change and impose sanctions
default. A 
defaultsubsta
defaultntially 
defaultreformed HMIC 
defaultcould perform
default this function.  The powers conferred on the Police and Crime Commissioners (PCC) to dismiss Chief Constables should ensure compliance. However it may be worth considering introducing legislation empowering the Home Secre
defaulttary to force the PCC to call an election if standards of crime recording are so poor 
defaultthat the public cannot have confidence in the data on which they are expected to judge the force’s performance
default.
default&#xa0;
default4.6default The pressure created by performance indicators to eng
defaultage in ‘gaming’ behaviours could be mitigated by a radical change in emphasis on what is measured.  If the performance measures on which forces are judged were qualitative 
defaultaudit results 
defaultand other quantitative data was viewed as for learning purposes it sho
defaultuld be possible to develop a knowledge based approach to policing. This approach 
defaultwas
default advocated by Jackson 
default(2005). 
default 
